  "description": "<section id=\"description\">\n<p>Let us call a positive integer $k$ a square-pivot, if there is a pair of integers $m > 0$ and $n ≥ k$, such that the sum of the ($m + 1$) consecutive squares up to $k$ equals the sum of the $m$ consecutive squares from ($n + 1$) on:</p>\n<p>$${(k - m)}^2 + \\ldots + k^2 = {(n + 1)}^2 + \\ldots + {(n + m)}^2$$</p>\n<p>Some small square-pivots are</p>\n<p>$$\\begin{align}\n&#x26; \\mathbf{4}: 3^2 + \\mathbf{4}^2 = 5^2 \\\\\n&#x26; \\mathbf{21}: {20}^2 + \\mathbf{21}^2 = {29}^2 \\\\\n&#x26; \\mathbf{24}: {21}^2 + {22}^2 + {23}^2 + \\mathbf{24}^2 = {25}^2 + {26}^2 + {27}^2 \\\\\n&#x26; \\mathbf{110}: {108}^2 + {109}^2 + \\mathbf{110}^2 = {133}^2 + {134}^2 \\\\\n\\end{align}$$</p>\n<p>Find the sum of all distinct square-pivots $≤ {10}^{10}$.</p>\n</section>",
